00:17:19.300 --> 00:17:21.460 align:middle line:90%
That's the quantum physics.

00:17:21.460 --> 00:17:23.780 align:middle line:84%
And the experiment
that I'm talking about

00:17:23.780 --> 00:17:27.790 align:middle line:84%
was known as the very,
very famous double slit

00:17:27.790 --> 00:17:30.770 align:middle line:90%
experiment, performed in 1909.

00:17:30.770 --> 00:17:34.270 align:middle line:84%
And the mystery is
because the result

00:17:34.270 --> 00:17:37.810 align:middle line:84%
of the double-slit
experiment actually

00:17:37.810 --> 00:17:41.380 align:middle line:84%
is determined by
whether or not someone

00:17:41.380 --> 00:17:44.784 align:middle line:90%
is watching the experiment, OK?

00:17:44.784 --> 00:17:45.700 align:middle line:90%
Let me say that again.

00:17:45.700 --> 00:17:47.620 align:middle line:84%
Let me tell you how
this experiment works.

00:17:47.620 --> 00:17:53.290 align:middle line:84%
The double-slit experiment
begins as a beam of photons.

00:17:53.290 --> 00:17:55.390 align:middle line:90%
And you see a common theme here.

00:17:55.390 --> 00:17:56.980 align:middle line:90%
We're talking about photons.

00:17:56.980 --> 00:18:00.790 align:middle line:84%
They are the elementary
stuff that atoms are made of,

00:18:00.790 --> 00:18:02.380 align:middle line:84%
the stuff our world
is made of you.

00:18:02.380 --> 00:18:04.330 align:middle line:90%
You and I are made of photons.

00:18:04.330 --> 00:18:05.620 align:middle line:90%
Our world is made of photons.

00:18:05.620 --> 00:18:08.290 align:middle line:84%
So it's not surprising that
they would be used a lot

00:18:08.290 --> 00:18:10.340 align:middle line:90%
throughout these experiments.

00:18:10.340 --> 00:18:15.100 align:middle line:84%
So in the double-slit
experiment, a beam of light,

00:18:15.100 --> 00:18:21.100 align:middle line:84%
photons, particles of light,
was fired from a device.

00:18:21.100 --> 00:18:24.190 align:middle line:90%
And it was fired at a barrier.

00:18:24.190 --> 00:18:28.630 align:middle line:84%
And the barrier had two
slits on either side.

00:18:28.630 --> 00:18:30.610 align:middle line:84%
And what scientists
expected to see

00:18:30.610 --> 00:18:34.000 align:middle line:84%
was that once the
light hit the barrier,

00:18:34.000 --> 00:18:37.180 align:middle line:84%
it would go through
both of the slits,

00:18:37.180 --> 00:18:39.700 align:middle line:84%
and we would be able to
see the patterns that

00:18:39.700 --> 00:18:44.150 align:middle line:84%
was creating in a very
expected way on the other side.

00:18:44.150 --> 00:18:46.940 align:middle line:84%
Well, this is where
the mystery comes in.

00:18:46.940 --> 00:18:49.480 align:middle line:84%
Because what scientists
found is that when

00:18:49.480 --> 00:18:54.610 align:middle line:84%
the light hit the barrier
and it went through

00:18:54.610 --> 00:18:57.970 align:middle line:84%
and it was being observed--
now, the observer

00:18:57.970 --> 00:18:59.080 align:middle line:90%
could be another human.

00:18:59.080 --> 00:19:01.480 align:middle line:84%
It could be a
device watching it.

00:19:01.480 --> 00:19:05.500 align:middle line:84%
But somehow, the
observation actually

00:19:05.500 --> 00:19:10.330 align:middle line:84%
determined how those particles
of light would behave.

00:19:10.330 --> 00:19:13.540 align:middle line:84%
When no one and
nothing was observing,

00:19:13.540 --> 00:19:16.000 align:middle line:84%
the particles would
behave in one way.

00:19:16.000 --> 00:19:19.900 align:middle line:84%
When someone or a
gadget was recording,

00:19:19.900 --> 00:19:22.660 align:middle line:84%
the particles would
behave in another way.

00:19:22.660 --> 00:19:24.040 align:middle line:90%
And here's the difference.

00:19:24.040 --> 00:19:26.080 align:middle line:84%
Under one set of
circumstances, the particles

00:19:26.080 --> 00:19:26.880 align:middle line:90%
