And this was actually reported
in a very prestigious journal

00:22:55.660 --> 00:23:00.340 align:middle line:84%
"Nature," February 26, 1998,
volume 391, if you want

00:23:00.340 --> 00:23:02.150 align:middle line:90%
to look it up for yourself.

00:23:02.150 --> 00:23:06.280 align:middle line:84%
This experiment is telling
us that not only are we

00:23:06.280 --> 00:23:10.600 align:middle line:84%
intimately enmeshed
with the world around us

00:23:10.600 --> 00:23:14.710 align:middle line:84%
and with the world within us,
but the more focus, the greater

00:23:14.710 --> 00:23:17.560 align:middle line:84%
our focus, the greater the
attention that we give,

00:23:17.560 --> 00:23:19.360 align:middle line:84%
specifically something
that's happening

00:23:19.360 --> 00:23:21.820 align:middle line:84%
in our lives, the
greater the effect.

00:23:21.820 --> 00:23:25.360 align:middle line:84%
But I think this is interesting,
because we already knew this

00:23:25.360 --> 00:23:27.075 align:middle line:84%
if we followed the
principles in some

00:23:27.075 --> 00:23:31.180 align:middle line:84%
of our most ancient, again, and
cherished spiritual traditions.

00:23:31.180 --> 00:23:36.970 align:middle line:84%
For example, in the Sutra
from the Mahayana Buddhist

00:23:36.970 --> 00:23:39.490 align:middle line:84%
traditions, there
is a statement that

00:23:39.490 --> 00:23:43.090 align:middle line:84%
essentially summarizes what
the Weitzman experience just

00:23:43.090 --> 00:23:44.050 align:middle line:90%
told us.

00:23:44.050 --> 00:23:48.670 align:middle line:84%
And that statement says,
quote, "Reality exists only

00:23:48.670 --> 00:23:51.820 align:middle line:84%
where the mind creates
a focus." "Reality

00:23:51.820 --> 00:23:54.640 align:middle line:84%
exists only where the
mind creates a focus."

00:23:54.640 --> 00:23:56.380 align:middle line:84%
So the ancient Buddhist
traditions, they

00:23:56.380 --> 00:23:57.850 align:middle line:84%
didn't have the
science, but they sure

00:23:57.850 --> 00:23:58.930 align:middle line:90%
understood the principle.

00:23:58.930 --> 00:24:00.640 align:middle line:90%
They understood the mechanism.

00:24:00.640 --> 00:24:05.450 align:middle line:84%
Where we create this
convergence of thought, feeling,

00:24:05.450 --> 00:24:09.130 align:middle line:84%
and emotion, where
we create that focus,

00:24:09.130 --> 00:24:12.340 align:middle line:84%
that is us observing
the world around us.

00:24:12.340 --> 00:24:16.580 align:middle line:84%
And it is that
experience and the fact

00:24:16.580 --> 00:24:20.870 align:middle line:84%
that that experience has such
a powerful effect in our lives

00:24:20.870 --> 00:24:22.760 align:middle line:84%
that actually made
Albert Einstein-- it

00:24:22.760 --> 00:24:24.660 align:middle line:90%
was making him crazy.

00:24:24.660 --> 00:24:28.160 align:middle line:84%
This is the piece of the
puzzle that Einstein was never

00:24:28.160 --> 00:24:29.840 align:middle line:90%
able to solve.

00:24:29.840 --> 00:24:32.060 align:middle line:10%
He began early in
the 20th century

00:24:32.060 --> 00:24:34.820 align:middle line:10%
with his theories of
relativity, and he was always

00:24:34.820 --> 00:24:40.539 align:middle line:10%
searching for a unified
theory, a unified field theory.

00:24:40.539 --> 00:24:41.830 align:middle line:90%
And here's what I mean by that.

00:24:41.830 --> 00:24:45.020 align:middle line:84%
A unified field theory
is where a scientist,

00:24:45.020 --> 00:24:49.730 align:middle line:84%
like Albert Einstein, creates a
single story that incorporates

00:24:49.730 --> 00:24:53.840 align:middle line:84%
all of the facets of nature
and physics and mathematics

00:24:53.840 --> 00:24:56.990 align:middle line:84%
into one coherent story
of us, our universe,

00:24:56.990 --> 00:24:58.680 align:middle line:90%
and our relationship to it.

00:24:58.680 --> 00:25:01.040 align:middle line:84%
The unified field theory
has been an elusive theory.

00:25:01.040 --> 00:25:03.710 align:middle line:90%
It has yet to be discovered.

00:25:03.710 --> 00:25:05.721 align:middle line:84%
And the world
supported Einstein,

00:25:05.721 --> 00:25:07.970 align:middle line:84%
thinking that this is the
man-- if anyone could do it,

00:25:07.970 --> 00:25:09.050 align:middle line:90%
he could do it.

00:25:09.050 --> 00:25:10.880 align:middle line:90%
Here's where Einstein got stuck.

00:25:10.880 --> 00:25:13.010 align:middle line:84%
And he actually admitted
this on his deathbed

00:25:13.010 --> 00:25:14.930 align:middle line:90%
in the early 1950s.

00:25:14.930 --> 00:25:20.360 align:middle line:84%
He got stuck because he did not
like the idea that we are so

00:25:20.360 --> 00:25:22.730 align:middle line:84%
intimately connected
with our universe

00:25:22.730 --> 00:25:25.850 align:middle line:84%
that we could have any
influence whatsoever

00:25:25.850 --> 00:25:30.260 align:middle line:84%
on the universe in one place
with us being in another place.

00:25:30.260 --> 00:25:32.760 align:middle line:84%
And as I mentioned earlier,
he actually had a name.

00:25:32.760 --> 00:25:37.010 align:middle line:84%
He called this "spooky
action at a distance."

00:25:37.010 --> 00:25:40.220 align:middle line:84%
He called this "spooky
action at a distance,"

00:25:40.220 --> 00:25:43.160 align:middle line:90%
because to him, it was spooky.

00:25:43.160 --> 00:25:45.920 align:middle line:84%
One of the things I find
particularly fascinating

00:25:45.920 --> 00:25:50.210 align:middle line:84%
is that although
Einstein was working

00:25:50.210 --> 00:25:52.970 align:middle line:84%
with the same mathematics
and the same equations

00:25:52.970 --> 00:25:57.110 align:middle line:84%
as his friends and colleagues,
he came to the conclusion

00:25:57.110 --> 00:25:59.870 align:middle line:84%
that we are separate
from one another

00:25:59.870 --> 00:26:02.600 align:middle line:84%
and that we are separate
from the universe

00:26:02.600 --> 00:26:05.430 align:middle line:84%
and that we can be
observers in the universe.

00:26:05.430 --> 00:26:08.360 align:middle line:84%
However, a dear
friend and colleague

00:26:08.360 --> 00:26:12.100 align:middle line:84%
of Albert Einstein's a man that
lived much longer than Einstein

00:26:12.100 --> 00:26:15.800 align:middle line:84%
and had a tremendously
powerful influence in quantum

00:26:15.800 --> 00:26:18.730 align:middle line:84%
physics at Princeton
University and our world today

00:26:18.730 --> 00:26:20.000 align:middle line:90%
was Professor John Wheeler.

00:26:20.000 --> 00:26:22.977 align:middle line:84%
He passed away just
a few years ago.

00:26:22.977 --> 00:26:25.310 align:middle line:10%
So John Wheeler and Albert
Einstein-- they were friends,

00:26:25.310 --> 00:26:27.435 align:middle line:10%
they were colleagues looking
at the same equations,

00:26:27.435 --> 00:26:31.860 align:middle line:10%
the same math, drawing
vastly different conclusions.

00:26:31.860 --> 00:26:34.160 align:middle line:10%
So while Einstein
believed that we're

00:26:34.160 --> 00:26:37.950 align:middle line:10%
separate and have no effect,
Wheeler said just the opposite.

00:26:37.950 --> 00:26:41.030 align:middle line:84%
And I want to share with you
John Wheeler's exact words

00:26:41.030 --> 00:26:44.990 align:middle line:84%
just so you can hear his
process and his thinking

00:26:44.990 --> 00:26:48.020 align:middle line:84%
and how passionate
he was about this.

00:26:48.020 --> 00:26:53.570 align:middle line:84%
John Wheeler said we had
this old idea that there is

00:26:53.570 --> 00:26:56.340 align:middle line:90%
a universe out there somewhere.

00:26:56.340 --> 00:27:00.530 align:middle line:84%
And here's man, what he
called the observer, safely

00:27:00.530 --> 00:27:04.400 align:middle line:84%
protected from the
universe by what he called

00:27:04.400 --> 00:27:07.720 align:middle line:90%
a six-inch slab of plate glass.

00:27:07.720 --> 00:27:09.770 align:middle line:84%
OK, so it's not
really plate glass,

00:27:09.770 --> 00:27:12.030 align:middle line:84%
but that is his way
of saying that there

00:27:12.030 --> 00:27:15.500 align:middle line:84%
is something between us
and the universe out there.

00:27:15.500 --> 00:27:16.790 align:middle line:90%
But he continues.

00:27:16.790 --> 00:27:21.350 align:middle line:84%
He said, now we learn that
to even observe an electron,

00:27:21.350 --> 00:27:23.570 align:middle line:84%
we have to shatter
that plate glass.

00:27:23.570 --> 00:27:24.990 align:middle line:90%
And listen to what he said.

00:27:24.990 --> 00:27:28.250 align:middle line:84%
He said, so the old
word "observer" simply

00:27:28.250 --> 00:27:30.410 align:middle line:90%
has to be crossed off the books.

00:27:30.410 --> 00:27:32.240 align:middle line:90%
He said, there are no observers.

00:27:32.240 --> 00:27:36.980 align:middle line:84%
We must put in the new word
"participator"-- no observers,

00:27:36.980 --> 00:27:38.320 align:middle line:90%
only participators.

00:27:38.320 --> 00:27:39.350 align:middle line:90%
So what does this mean?

00:27:39.350 --> 00:27:42.620 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to just
very, very quickly

00:27:42.620 --> 00:27:46.810 align:middle line:84%
encapsulate this idea of why
it's so powerful in our lives.

00:27:46.810 --> 00:27:48.560 align:middle line:84%
Because what John
Wheeler has just said to

00:27:48.560 --> 00:27:53.030 align:middle line:84%
us tells us that we will never
find the smallest particle

00:27:53.030 --> 00:27:57.290 align:middle line:84%
of matter, no matter how many
atoms and quantum particles

00:27:57.290 --> 00:27:59.180 align:middle line:84%
that we smash into
one another and break

00:27:59.180 --> 00:28:02.240 align:middle line:84%
into a bajillion pieces looking
for smaller smaller pieces.

00:28:02.240 --> 00:28:05.210 align:middle line:84%
And we will never find
the edge of the universe,

00:28:05.210 --> 00:28:08.660 align:middle line:84%
no matter how far we look
to the edge of the cosmos

00:28:08.660 --> 00:28:11.980 align:middle line:84%
and how technologically
sophisticated our equipment is.

00:28:11.980 --> 00:28:13.310 align:middle line:90%
And here's the reason why.

00:28:13.310 --> 00:28:15.530 align:middle line:84%
What John Wheeler
just said to us

00:28:15.530 --> 00:28:22.700 align:middle line:84%
is that every place that we look
into the universe, every place

00:28:22.700 --> 00:28:26.810 align:middle line:84%
that we look into nature with
the expectation that something

00:28:26.810 --> 00:28:30.350 align:middle line:84%
is there for us to
see, the expectation

00:28:30.350 --> 00:28:34.580 align:middle line:84%
is the principle that will put
something there for us to see.

00:28:34.580 --> 00:28:38.390 align:middle line:84%
So no matter how far, no matter
how deep, as long as we're

00:28:38.390 --> 00:28:42.140 align:middle line:84%
looking, the act of looking
is the act of creation

00:28:42.140 --> 00:28:44.420 align:middle line:84%
that makes sure there
will always be something

00:28:44.420 --> 00:28:47.120 align:middle line:90%
there for us to see.

00:28:47.120 --> 00:28:51.050 align:middle line:84%
So what we've just witnessed are
the science-based experiments

00:28:51.050 --> 00:28:54.200 align:middle line:84%
and the real-life application
of these experiments

00:28:54.200 --> 00:28:58.250 align:middle line:84%
